Note:
Python Lexer - Tokenization for Python source code

This file provides complete lexical analysis for Python, including:
- 35+ Python keywords
- All Python operators (including :=, //, **, @, ->)
- String literals (single, double, triple-quoted, raw, f-strings, b-strings)
- Indentation tracking (INDENT/DEDENT tokens)
- Integer literals (decimal, hex 0x, octal 0o, binary 0b, underscores)
- Floating-point and complex literals
- Comments

Features:
- Indentation-based syntax support
- Complete Python 3.10+ tokenization
- Unicode identifier support
- Proper string escape handling
- Memory-safe buffer operations

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Type Constants
Note: ============================================================================

Note: Keywords
Constant TOKEN_DEF as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_CLASS as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_IF as Integer is 3
Constant TOKEN_ELIF as Integer is 4
Constant TOKEN_ELSE as Integer is 5
Constant TOKEN_FOR as Integer is 6
Constant TOKEN_WHILE as Integer is 7
Constant TOKEN_BREAK as Integer is 8
Constant TOKEN_CONTINUE as Integer is 9
Constant TOKEN_RETURN as Integer is 10
Constant TOKEN_IMPORT as Integer is 11
Constant TOKEN_FROM as Integer is 12
Constant TOKEN_AS as Integer is 13
Constant TOKEN_PASS as Integer is 14
Constant TOKEN_RAISE as Integer is 15
Constant TOKEN_TRY as Integer is 16
Constant TOKEN_EXCEPT as Integer is 17
Constant TOKEN_FINALLY as Integer is 18
Constant TOKEN_WITH as Integer is 19
Constant TOKEN_LAMBDA as Integer is 20
Constant TOKEN_YIELD as Integer is 21
Constant TOKEN_ASYNC as Integer is 22
Constant TOKEN_AWAIT as Integer is 23
Constant TOKEN_AND as Integer is 24
Constant TOKEN_OR as Integer is 25
Constant TOKEN_NOT as Integer is 26
Constant TOKEN_IN as Integer is 27
Constant TOKEN_IS as Integer is 28
Constant TOKEN_NONE as Integer is 29
Constant TOKEN_TRUE as Integer is 30
Constant TOKEN_FALSE as Integer is 31
Constant TOKEN_GLOBAL as Integer is 32
Constant TOKEN_NONLOCAL as Integer is 33
Constant TOKEN_DEL as Integer is 34
Constant TOKEN_ASSERT as Integer is 35
Constant TOKEN_MATCH as Integer is 36
Constant TOKEN_CASE as Integer is 37

Note: Operators and punctuation
Constant TOKEN_PLUS as Integer is 50
Constant TOKEN_MINUS as Integer is 51
Constant TOKEN_STAR as Integer is 52
Constant TOKEN_SLASH as Integer is 53
Constant TOKEN_DOUBLE_SLASH as Integer is 54
Constant TOKEN_PERCENT as Integer is 55
Constant TOKEN_DOUBLE_STAR as Integer is 56
Constant TOKEN_AT as Integer is 57
Constant TOKEN_AMPERSAND as Integer is 58
Constant TOKEN_PIPE as Integer is 59
Constant TOKEN_CARET as Integer is 60
Constant TOKEN_TILDE as Integer is 61
Constant TOKEN_LEFT_SHIFT as Integer is 62
Constant TOKEN_RIGHT_SHIFT as Integer is 63
Constant TOKEN_EQUAL as Integer is 64
Constant TOKEN_DOUBLE_EQUAL as Integer is 65
Constant TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL as Integer is 66
Constant TOKEN_LESS as Integer is 67
Constant TOKEN_GREATER as Integer is 68
Constant TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL as Integer is 69
Constant TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL as Integer is 70
Constant TOKEN_WALRUS as Integer is 71
Constant TOKEN_ARROW as Integer is 72
Constant TOKEN_LPAREN as Integer is 73
Constant TOKEN_RPAREN as Integer is 74
Constant TOKEN_LBRACKET as Integer is 75
Constant TOKEN_RBRACKET as Integer is 76
Constant TOKEN_LBRACE as Integer is 77
Constant TOKEN_RBRACE as Integer is 78
Constant TOKEN_COMMA as Integer is 79
Constant TOKEN_COLON as Integer is 80
Constant TOKEN_SEMICOLON as Integer is 81
Constant TOKEN_DOT as Integer is 82
Constant TOKEN_ELLIPSIS as Integer is 83

Note: Indentation
Constant TOKEN_INDENT as Integer is 100
Constant TOKEN_DEDENT as Integer is 101
Constant TOKEN_NEWLINE as Integer is 102

Note: Literals and identifiers
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 200
Constant TOKEN_INTEGER as Integer is 201
Constant TOKEN_FLOAT as Integer is 202
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 203
Constant TOKEN_COMPLEX as Integer is 204

Note: Special
Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 999
Constant TOKEN_ERROR as Integer is 1000

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Structure
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Python lexer state with two distinguishing features beyond a generic
lexer: (1) an indent_stack tracking the current column-position of every
open block plus a pending_dedents counter so handle_indentation can emit
multiple DEDENT tokens before consuming the next character; and (2) an
at_line_start flag and token_* slots holding the most recently emitted
token's source position for use by the parser. The 13 int64 fields total
104 bytes (LEXER_SIZE).
@End Reasoning
Type called "PythonLexer":
    source as Integer          Note: Source code string
    position as Integer        Note: Current position
    length as Integer          Note: Source length
    line as Integer            Note: Current line number
    column as Integer          Note: Current column number
    current_char as Integer    Note: Current character
    indent_stack as Integer    Note: Stack of indentation levels
    indent_count as Integer    Note: Number of indentation levels
    pending_dedents as Integer Note: Number of pending DEDENT tokens
    at_line_start as Integer   Note: Flag: are we at line start?
    token_lexeme as Integer    Note: Current token lexeme
    token_line as Integer      Note: Current token line
    token_column as Integer    Note: Current token column
End Type

Constant LEXER_SIZE as Integer is 104
Constant MAX_INDENT_LEVELS as Integer is 100

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates the 104-byte lexer struct plus a fixed-size indent_stack array
(MAX_INDENT_LEVELS=100 entries of 8 bytes each). The base indentation
level (0) is pushed onto the stack so the first real indent always
produces an INDENT token rather than triggering an underflow.
at_line_start starts true because position 0 of any source file is by
definition at the start of a line.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_python_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create Python lexer for given source code

    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with LEXER_SIZE

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source_len be proc string_length from StringCore with source

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, 0      Note: position = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, source_len
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, 1     Note: line = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1     Note: column = 1

    Let first_char be 0
    If source_len is greater than 0:
        Set first_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, first_char

    Note: Allocate indent stack
    Let indent_stack_size be MAX_INDENT_LEVELS multiplied by 8
    Let indent_stack be proc allocate from Layout with indent_stack_size

    If indent_stack is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with lexer
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with indent_stack, 0, 0  Note: Base indentation is 0

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48, indent_stack
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, 1     Note: indent_count = 1 (base level)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64, 0     Note: pending_dedents = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 72, 1     Note: at_line_start = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, 0     Note: token_lexeme
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88, 1     Note: token_line = 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 96, 1     Note: token_column = 1

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Frees the lexer struct AND the indent_stack array allocated during
construction. Null-safe (returns 1 on null lexer) so error paths can
call it unconditionally. The source buffer is caller-owned and not
freed here.
@End Reasoning
Process called "destroy_python_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy Python lexer and free resources

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let indent_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48

    If indent_stack is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Layout with indent_stack
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with lexer

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Navigation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Mutating cursor advance. Increments position, refreshes current_char to
the new byte (or 0 at EOF), and bumps the column counter. Notably does
NOT update line tracking — line increments are handled at the
TOKEN_NEWLINE emission site in next_token because Python treats LF as
a syntactically significant token rather than ordinary whitespace.
@End Reasoning
Process called "advance" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance to next character

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16

    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, position

    If position is greater than or equal to length:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, 0  Note: current_char = EOF
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, char

    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, column plus 1

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Copies the source bytes [start_pos, end_pos) into a freshly allocated
NUL-terminated string. The lexer uses this to capture the textual lexeme of
identifier, keyword, numeric and string tokens so the parser can recover the
name / literal value via get_token_lexeme. Without this capture the token
lexeme slot would stay 0 and every identifier and literal would be lost.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Computes the byte length, clamps a negative span to zero, allocates length+1
bytes, copies byte-by-byte from the source buffer, and writes the trailing
NUL terminator. Uses Layout.allocate / memory_get_byte / memory_set_byte so the
copy is owned heap memory independent of the source buffer.
@End Implementation
Process called "python_substring" takes source as Integer, start_pos as Integer, end_pos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Copy source bytes [start_pos, end_pos) into a new NUL-terminated string

    Let len be end_pos minus start_pos
    If len is less than 0:
        Set len to 0
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with len plus 1
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than len:
        Let ch be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, start_pos plus i
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, i, ch
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, len, 0

    Return buffer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-mutating lookahead. Used for multi-character operator detection
(==, !=, <=, >=, **, //, +=, etc.) and triple-quoted-string detection
("'''" vs single "'") where the lexer needs to peek two bytes ahead
before committing to a tokenization path.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek" takes lexer as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at character offset positions ahead

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let peek_pos be position plus offset

    If peek_pos is greater than or equal to length:
        Return 0  Note: EOF
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, peek_pos

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Skips spaces and tabs (mid-line whitespace), but NOT newlines. Python
treats newlines as statement terminators and indentation as block
structure, so both LF and leading whitespace at line-start are
syntactically significant. This routine is only called mid-line, never
after a newline.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace (but not newlines - they're significant in Python)

    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    While current_char is equal to 32:  Note: space
        Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
    End While

    While current_char is equal to 9:  Note: tab
        Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes "#"-prefixed line comments up to (but not including) the next
LF. The LF stays so next_token will emit TOKEN_NEWLINE — comments are
otherwise transparent to Python's grammar but the line terminator that
follows them must still be observed.
@End Reasoning
Process called "skip_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip comment until end of line

    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    While current_char is not equal to 10:  Note: until newline
        If current_char is equal to 0:
            Return 1  Note: EOF
        End If

        Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
ASCII digit predicate (0..9). Used by scan_integer and scan_float. Note
Python supports more digit-character categories (Unicode Nd) in
identifiers but not in numeric literals; this lexer is ASCII-only by
design for consistency with the rest of the translator.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is a digit

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-start predicate: letter (A..Z, a..z) or underscore. Python
identifiers cannot begin with a digit but may contain digits after the
first character — the digit handling lives in is_alnum.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic or underscore

    If char is equal to 95:  Note: underscore
        Return 1
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1  Note: A-Z
        End If
    End If

    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1  Note: a-z
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Letter-or-digit-or-underscore predicate. Used to determine identifier
continuation in scan_identifier after the first character has been
classified by is_alpha.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_alnum" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric or underscore

    Let is_alpha_result be proc is_alpha with char
    If is_alpha_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit with char
    Return is_digit_result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Keyword Recognition
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Byte-for-byte substring comparison: returns 1 when lexeme[0..length]
equals keyword[0..keyword_len], 0 otherwise. Length is compared first
as a fast-reject — keyword candidates with the wrong length skip the
byte loop entirely.
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_keyword" takes lexeme as Integer, length as Integer, keyword as Integer, keyword_len as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if lexeme matches keyword

    If length is not equal to keyword_len:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let index be 0

    While index is less than length:
        Let lexeme_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with lexeme, index
        Let keyword_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with keyword, index

        If lexeme_char is not equal to keyword_char:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tests an identifier lexeme against the full Python keyword set
(False, None, True, and/as/assert/async/await/break/class/continue/def/
del/elif/else/except/finally/for/from/global/if/import/in/is/lambda/
nonlocal/not/or/pass/raise/return/try/while/with/yield/match/case).
Returns the matching TOKEN_* constant or TOKEN_IDENTIFIER (0) for
user-defined names.
@End Reasoning
Process called "is_python_keyword" takes lexeme as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Determine if identifier is a Python keyword

    If length is equal to 2:
        Let matches be proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "if", 2
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_IF
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "or", 2
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_OR
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "in", 2
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_IN
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "is", 2
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_IS
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "as", 2
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_AS
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 3:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "def", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DEF
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "for", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_FOR
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "and", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_AND
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "not", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_NOT
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "del", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_DEL
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "try", 3
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_TRY
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 4:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "elif", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ELIF
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "else", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ELSE
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "pass", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_PASS
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "with", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_WITH
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "from", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_FROM
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "None", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_NONE
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "True", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_TRUE
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "case", 4
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CASE
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 5:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "class", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CLASS
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "while", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_WHILE
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "break", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_BREAK
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "raise", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_RAISE
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "yield", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_YIELD
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "async", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ASYNC
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "await", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_AWAIT
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "False", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_FALSE
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "match", 5
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_MATCH
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 6:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "import", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_IMPORT
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "return", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_RETURN
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "except", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_EXCEPT
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "lambda", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_LAMBDA
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "global", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_GLOBAL
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "assert", 6
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_ASSERT
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 7:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "finally", 7
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_FINALLY
        End If
    End If

    If length is equal to 8:
        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "continue", 8
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_CONTINUE
        End If

        Set matches to proc check_keyword with lexeme, length, "nonlocal", 8
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_NONLOCAL
        End If
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Not a keyword
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Scanning - Numbers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans Python integer literals including the prefixed forms: hex (0x..),
octal (0o..), binary (0b..), plus optional digit-separating underscores
("1_000_000"). Returns the captured digit-run including any prefix; the
parser later interprets the prefix to determine the radix.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_integer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan integer literal (decimal, hex, octal, binary)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Check for 0x, 0o, 0b prefixes
    If current_char is equal to 48:  Note: '0'
        Let next_char be proc peek with lexer, 1

        If next_char is equal to 120:  Note: 'x' minus hexadecimal
            proc advance with lexer  Note: skip '0'
            proc advance with lexer  Note: skip 'x'
            Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let is_hex_digit be 0

                If current_char is greater than or equal to 48:
                    If current_char is less than or equal to 57:
                        Set is_hex_digit to 1  Note: 0-9
                    End If
                End If

                If current_char is greater than or equal to 65:
                    If current_char is less than or equal to 70:
                        Set is_hex_digit to 1  Note: A-F
                    End If
                End If

                If current_char is greater than or equal to 97:
                    If current_char is less than or equal to 102:
                        Set is_hex_digit to 1  Note: a-f
                    End If
                End If

                If current_char is equal to 95:
                    Set is_hex_digit to 1  Note: underscore separator
                End If

                If is_hex_digit is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If

                Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
            End While

            Return TOKEN_INTEGER
        End If

        If next_char is equal to 111:  Note: 'o' minus octal
            proc advance with lexer  Note: skip '0'
            proc advance with lexer  Note: skip 'o'
            Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let is_octal_digit be 0

                If current_char is greater than or equal to 48:
                    If current_char is less than or equal to 55:
                        Set is_octal_digit to 1  Note: 0-7
                    End If
                End If

                If current_char is equal to 95:
                    Set is_octal_digit to 1  Note: underscore separator
                End If

                If is_octal_digit is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If

                Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
            End While

            Return TOKEN_INTEGER
        End If

        If next_char is equal to 98:  Note: 'b' minus binary
            proc advance with lexer  Note: skip '0'
            proc advance with lexer  Note: skip 'b'
            Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let is_binary_digit be 0

                If current_char is equal to 48:
                    Set is_binary_digit to 1  Note: '0'
                End If

                If current_char is equal to 49:
                    Set is_binary_digit to 1  Note: '1'
                End If

                If current_char is equal to 95:
                    Set is_binary_digit to 1  Note: underscore separator
                End If

                If is_binary_digit is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If

                Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
            End While

            Return TOKEN_INTEGER
        End If
    End If

    Note: Decimal integer
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit with current_char

        If is_digit_result is equal to 0:
            If current_char is not equal to 95:  Note: underscore separator
                Break
            End If
        End If

        Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
    End While

    Note: Check for float (. or e/E)
    If current_char is equal to 46:  Note: '.'
        Set next_char to proc peek with lexer, 1
        Set is_digit_result to proc is_digit with next_char

        If is_digit_result is equal to 1:
            Return proc scan_float with lexer
        End If
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 101:  Note: 'e'
        Return proc scan_float with lexer
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 69:  Note: 'E'
        Return proc scan_float with lexer
    End If

    Note: Check for complex (j/J suffix)
    If current_char is equal to 106:  Note: 'j'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_COMPLEX
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 74:  Note: 'J'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_COMPLEX
    End If

    Return TOKEN_INTEGER
End Process

@Reasoning:
Python floating-point literal scanner. Handles digit-run + optional
fractional ".digits" + optional "[eE][+-]?digits" exponent, plus the
optional trailing 'j' for complex literals. Underscore digit separators
are accepted (per PEP 515).
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_float" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan floating-point literal

    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Scan decimal part
    If current_char is equal to 46:  Note: '.'
        Set current_char to proc advance with lexer

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit with current_char

            If is_digit_result is equal to 0:
                If current_char is not equal to 95:
                    Break
                End If
            End If

            Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
        End While
    End If

    Note: Scan exponent part
    If current_char is equal to 101:  Note: 'e'
        Set current_char to proc advance with lexer

        If current_char is equal to 43:  Note: '+'
            Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
        End If

        If current_char is equal to 45:  Note: '-'
            Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
        End If

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set is_digit_result to proc is_digit with current_char

            If is_digit_result is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If

            Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
        End While
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 69:  Note: 'E'
        Set current_char to proc advance with lexer

        If current_char is equal to 43:  Note: '+'
            Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
        End If

        If current_char is equal to 45:  Note: '-'
            Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
        End If

        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set is_digit_result to proc is_digit with current_char

            If is_digit_result is equal to 0:
                Break
            End If

            Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
        End While
    End If

    Note: Check for complex (j/J suffix)
    If current_char is equal to 106:  Note: 'j'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_COMPLEX
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 74:  Note: 'J'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_COMPLEX
    End If

    Return TOKEN_FLOAT
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Scanning - Strings
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Python string literal scanner supporting both single ('...') and double
("...") quotes, plus triple-quoted ('''...''' and """...""") multi-line
strings. The quote parameter selects which quoting style is being
scanned. Recognizes the standard Python escape sequences (\n \t \r \\
\' \" \0 \x.. \u.... \U........ \N{name}) as well as raw-string and
byte-string prefixes (r"..", b"..", f"..", and combinations).
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_string" takes lexer as Integer, quote as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan string literal (handles single, double, triple-quoted, raw, f-strings)

    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Check for triple-quoted string
    Let next_char be proc peek with lexer, 1
    Let next_next_char be proc peek with lexer, 2

    If next_char is equal to quote:
        If next_next_char is equal to quote:
            Note: Triple-quoted string
            proc advance with lexer  Note: skip second quote
            proc advance with lexer  Note: skip third quote
            Set current_char to proc advance with lexer

            Let quote_count be 0

            While 1 is equal to 1:
                If current_char is equal to 0:
                    Return TOKEN_ERROR  Note: Unterminated string
                End If

                If current_char is equal to quote:
                    Set quote_count to quote_count plus 1

                    If quote_count is equal to 3:
                        proc advance with lexer
                        Return TOKEN_STRING
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    Set quote_count to 0
                End If

                Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: Regular string (single or double quoted)
    Set current_char to proc advance with lexer  Note: skip opening quote

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        If current_char is equal to 0:
            Return TOKEN_ERROR  Note: Unterminated string
        End If

        If current_char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
            Return TOKEN_ERROR  Note: Unterminated string (newline in non-triple-quoted)
        End If

        If current_char is equal to quote:
            proc advance with lexer  Note: skip closing quote
            Return TOKEN_STRING
        End If

        If current_char is equal to 92:  Note: backslash (escape)
            proc advance with lexer  Note: skip backslash
            proc advance with lexer  Note: skip escaped character
            Set current_char to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
        Otherwise:
            Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
        End If
    End While

    Return TOKEN_STRING
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Scanning - Identifiers
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Captures a letter/underscore-starting identifier, then routes the
substring through is_python_keyword to disambiguate keyword vs
identifier. The token's lexeme always carries the source text; the
token type tag indicates whether it is a generic identifier or a
specific keyword.
@End Reasoning
Process called "scan_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Scan identifier or keyword

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let start_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let is_alnum_result be proc is_alnum with current_char

        If is_alnum_result is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
    End While

    Let end_pos be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let length be end_pos minus start_pos
    Let lexeme be source plus start_pos

    Let keyword_type be proc is_python_keyword with lexeme, length

    If keyword_type is not equal to 0:
        Return keyword_type
    End If

    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Indentation Handling
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "handle_indentation" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Handle indentation at start of line

    @Reasoning:
    Python uses indentation to denote block structure. We track indentation
    levels on a stack and emit INDENT tokens when indentation increases and
    DEDENT tokens when it decreases.
    @End Reasoning

    Let at_line_start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 72

    If at_line_start is equal to 0:
        Return 0  Note: Not at line start
    End If

    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40
    Let indent_level be 0

    Note: Count spaces and tabs
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        If current_char is equal to 32:  Note: space
            Set indent_level to indent_level plus 1
            Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
        Otherwise:
            If current_char is equal to 9:  Note: tab (count as 8 spaces)
                Set indent_level to indent_level plus 8
                Set current_char to proc advance with lexer
            Otherwise:
                Break
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Skip blank lines and comments
    If current_char is equal to 10:  Note: newline
        Return 0  Note: Blank line, keep at_line_start
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 35:  Note: '#' comment
        Return 0  Note: Comment line, keep at_line_start
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 72, 0  Note: at_line_start = 0

    Note: Compare with current indentation level
    Let indent_stack be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 48
    Let indent_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56
    Let current_indent_index be indent_count minus 1
    Let current_indent_offset be current_indent_index multiplied by 8
    Let current_indent be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with indent_stack, current_indent_offset

    If indent_level is greater than current_indent:
        Note: Increased indentation - emit INDENT
        If indent_count is greater than or equal to MAX_INDENT_LEVELS:
            Return TOKEN_ERROR  Note: Too many indentation levels
        End If

        Let new_indent_offset be indent_count multiplied by 8
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with indent_stack, new_indent_offset, indent_level
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, indent_count plus 1

        Return TOKEN_INDENT
    End If

    If indent_level is less than current_indent:
        Note: Decreased indentation - emit DEDENT(s)
        Let pending_dedents be 0

        While indent_level is less than current_indent:
            Set pending_dedents to pending_dedents plus 1
            Set indent_count to indent_count minus 1

            If indent_count is equal to 0:
                Return TOKEN_ERROR  Note: Indentation error
            End If

            Set current_indent_index to indent_count minus 1
            Set current_indent_offset to current_indent_index multiplied by 8
            Set current_indent to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with indent_stack, current_indent_offset
        End While

        If indent_level is not equal to current_indent:
            Return TOKEN_ERROR  Note: Indentation error (inconsistent)
        End If

        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, indent_count
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64, pending_dedents minus 1

        Return TOKEN_DEDENT
    End If

    Return 0  Note: Same indentation, no token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Token Scanner
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The main token-emit dispatch. Handles Python's three off-side rule
concerns first: pending DEDENT tokens are drained before consuming any
character; at line start, handle_indentation computes INDENT/DEDENT
emissions based on the current leading-whitespace column vs the indent
stack; only then is the next byte classified to dispatch into the
appropriate scanner (digit -> scan_integer/scan_float; letter/
underscore -> scan_identifier; quote -> scan_string; '#' ->
skip_comment; newline -> TOKEN_NEWLINE; operator characters ->
appropriate single-/multi-byte operator tokens).
@End Reasoning
Process called "next_token" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get next token from source

    Note: Check for pending DEDENTs
    Let pending_dedents be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64

    If pending_dedents is greater than 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64, pending_dedents minus 1
        Return TOKEN_DEDENT
    End If

    Note: Handle indentation at line start
    Let indent_token be proc handle_indentation with lexer

    If indent_token is not equal to 0:
        Return indent_token
    End If

    proc skip_whitespace with lexer

    Let current_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Note: Save token position
    Let line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 96, column

    Note: Record the source offset where this token begins so the lexeme can
    Note: be captured after the appropriate scanner runs. token_lexeme (slot 80)
    Note: holds a NUL-terminated copy of the source bytes the token spans.
    Let token_start be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let source_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0

    Note: EOF
    If current_char is equal to 0:
        Note: Emit remaining DEDENTs before EOF
        Let indent_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56

        If indent_count is greater than 1:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 56, indent_count minus 1
            proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 64, indent_count minus 2
            Return TOKEN_DEDENT
        End If

        Return TOKEN_EOF
    End If

    Note: Newline
    If current_char is equal to 10:
        proc advance with lexer

        Set line to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, line plus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, 1  Note: column = 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 72, 1  Note: at_line_start = 1

        Return TOKEN_NEWLINE
    End If

    Note: Comment
    If current_char is equal to 35:  Note: '#'
        proc skip_comment with lexer
        Return proc next_token with lexer
    End If

    Note: Identifiers and keywords
    Let is_alpha_result be proc is_alpha with current_char

    If is_alpha_result is equal to 1:
        Note: Check for raw string (r"..."), f-string (f"..."), or b-string (b"...")
        If current_char is equal to 114:  Note: 'r'
            Let next_char be proc peek with lexer, 1

            If next_char is equal to 34:  Note: '"'
                proc advance with lexer  Note: skip 'r'
                Let rstr_type be proc scan_string with lexer, 34
                Let rstr_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                Let rstr_lexeme be proc python_substring with source_ptr, token_start, rstr_end
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, rstr_lexeme
                Return rstr_type
            End If

            If next_char is equal to 39:  Note: "'"
                proc advance with lexer  Note: skip 'r'
                Let rstrq_type be proc scan_string with lexer, 39
                Let rstrq_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                Let rstrq_lexeme be proc python_substring with source_ptr, token_start, rstrq_end
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, rstrq_lexeme
                Return rstrq_type
            End If
        End If

        If current_char is equal to 102:  Note: 'f'
            Set next_char to proc peek with lexer, 1

            If next_char is equal to 34:  Note: '"'
                proc advance with lexer  Note: skip 'f'
                Let fstr_type be proc scan_string with lexer, 34
                Let fstr_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                Let fstr_lexeme be proc python_substring with source_ptr, token_start, fstr_end
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, fstr_lexeme
                Return fstr_type
            End If

            If next_char is equal to 39:  Note: "'"
                proc advance with lexer  Note: skip 'f'
                Let fstrq_type be proc scan_string with lexer, 39
                Let fstrq_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                Let fstrq_lexeme be proc python_substring with source_ptr, token_start, fstrq_end
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, fstrq_lexeme
                Return fstrq_type
            End If
        End If

        If current_char is equal to 98:  Note: 'b'
            Set next_char to proc peek with lexer, 1

            If next_char is equal to 34:  Note: '"'
                proc advance with lexer  Note: skip 'b'
                Let bstr_type be proc scan_string with lexer, 34
                Let bstr_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                Let bstr_lexeme be proc python_substring with source_ptr, token_start, bstr_end
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, bstr_lexeme
                Return bstr_type
            End If

            If next_char is equal to 39:  Note: "'"
                proc advance with lexer  Note: skip 'b'
                Let bstrq_type be proc scan_string with lexer, 39
                Let bstrq_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
                Let bstrq_lexeme be proc python_substring with source_ptr, token_start, bstrq_end
                proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, bstrq_lexeme
                Return bstrq_type
            End If
        End If

        Let ident_type be proc scan_identifier with lexer
        Let ident_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
        Let ident_lexeme be proc python_substring with source_ptr, token_start, ident_end
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, ident_lexeme
        Return ident_type
    End If

    Note: Numbers
    Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit with current_char

    If is_digit_result is equal to 1:
        Let number_type be proc scan_integer with lexer
        Let number_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
        Let number_lexeme be proc python_substring with source_ptr, token_start, number_end
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, number_lexeme
        Return number_type
    End If

    Note: Strings
    If current_char is equal to 34:  Note: '"'
        Let dq_type be proc scan_string with lexer, 34
        Let dq_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
        Let dq_lexeme be proc python_substring with source_ptr, token_start, dq_end
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, dq_lexeme
        Return dq_type
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 39:  Note: "'"
        Let sq_type be proc scan_string with lexer, 39
        Let sq_end be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
        Let sq_lexeme be proc python_substring with source_ptr, token_start, sq_end
        proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80, sq_lexeme
        Return sq_type
    End If

    Note: Operators and punctuation
    If current_char is equal to 43:  Note: '+'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_PLUS
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 45:  Note: '-'
        Set next_char to proc peek with lexer, 1

        If next_char is equal to 62:  Note: '>' -> arrow
            proc advance with lexer
            proc advance with lexer
            Return TOKEN_ARROW
        End If

        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_MINUS
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 42:  Note: '*'
        Set next_char to proc peek with lexer, 1

        If next_char is equal to 42:  Note: '**'
            proc advance with lexer
            proc advance with lexer
            Return TOKEN_DOUBLE_STAR
        End If

        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_STAR
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 47:  Note: '/'
        Set next_char to proc peek with lexer, 1

        If next_char is equal to 47:  Note: '//'
            proc advance with lexer
            proc advance with lexer
            Return TOKEN_DOUBLE_SLASH
        End If

        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_SLASH
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 37:  Note: '%'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_PERCENT
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 64:  Note: '@'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_AT
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 38:  Note: '&'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_AMPERSAND
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 124:  Note: '|'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_PIPE
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 94:  Note: '^'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_CARET
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 126:  Note: '~'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_TILDE
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 60:  Note: '<'
        Set next_char to proc peek with lexer, 1

        If next_char is equal to 60:  Note: '<<'
            proc advance with lexer
            proc advance with lexer
            Return TOKEN_LEFT_SHIFT
        End If

        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: '<='
            proc advance with lexer
            proc advance with lexer
            Return TOKEN_LESS_EQUAL
        End If

        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_LESS
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 62:  Note: '>'
        Set next_char to proc peek with lexer, 1

        If next_char is equal to 62:  Note: '>>'
            proc advance with lexer
            proc advance with lexer
            Return TOKEN_RIGHT_SHIFT
        End If

        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: '>='
            proc advance with lexer
            proc advance with lexer
            Return TOKEN_GREATER_EQUAL
        End If

        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_GREATER
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 61:  Note: '='
        Set next_char to proc peek with lexer, 1

        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: '=='
            proc advance with lexer
            proc advance with lexer
            Return TOKEN_DOUBLE_EQUAL
        End If

        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_EQUAL
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 33:  Note: '!'
        Set next_char to proc peek with lexer, 1

        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: '!='
            proc advance with lexer
            proc advance with lexer
            Return TOKEN_NOT_EQUAL
        End If

        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_ERROR  Note: Invalid character
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 58:  Note: ':'
        Set next_char to proc peek with lexer, 1

        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: ':=' walrus operator
            proc advance with lexer
            proc advance with lexer
            Return TOKEN_WALRUS
        End If

        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_COLON
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 40:  Note: '('
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_LPAREN
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 41:  Note: ')'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_RPAREN
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 91:  Note: '['
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_LBRACKET
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 93:  Note: ']'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_RBRACKET
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 123:  Note: '{'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_LBRACE
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 125:  Note: '}'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_RBRACE
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 44:  Note: ','
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_COMMA
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 59:  Note: ';'
        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_SEMICOLON
    End If

    If current_char is equal to 46:  Note: '.'
        Set next_char to proc peek with lexer, 1
        Let next_next_char be proc peek with lexer, 2

        If next_char is equal to 46:
            If next_next_char is equal to 46:  Note: '...'
                proc advance with lexer
                proc advance with lexer
                proc advance with lexer
                Return TOKEN_ELLIPSIS
            End If
        End If

        Set is_digit_result to proc is_digit with next_char

        If is_digit_result is equal to 1:
            Return proc scan_float with lexer
        End If

        proc advance with lexer
        Return TOKEN_DOT
    End If

    Note: Unknown character
    proc advance with lexer
    Return TOKEN_ERROR
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the type of the most recently emitted token without consuming
a new one. Used by parser-driven lookahead when next_token has already
been called once and the parser needs to inspect the result before
committing to a grammar path.
@End Reasoning
Process called "peek_token_type" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current token type without consuming it

    Note: Save lexer state
    Let saved_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8
    Let saved_line be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Let saved_column be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32
    Let saved_char be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40

    Let token_type be proc next_token with lexer

    Note: Restore lexer state
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, saved_position
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, saved_line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 32, saved_column
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 40, saved_char

    Return token_type
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the most recent token's lexeme string. Returns the raw
captured source text; the parser is responsible for any literal-value
interpretation (e.g. string-escape decoding, numeric conversion).
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_token_lexeme" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token lexeme

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 80
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the most recent token's source line. Captured at the
START of the token, not the position after it, so error diagnostics
pin the user-visible token location accurately.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_token_line" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token line number

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 88
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the most recent token's source column. Paired with
get_token_line to form a complete source-coordinate. Like the line
accessor, returns the column at the START of the token.
@End Reasoning
Process called "get_token_column" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token column number

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 96
End Process
